    can be used in a GStreamer pipeline. Please refer to the plugin writers
    guide for more information on creating :class:`Gst.Element` subclasses.

    The name of a :class:`Gst.Element` can be get with gst_element_get_name() and set with
    gst_element_set_name().  For speed, GST_ELEMENT_NAME() can be used in the
    core when using the appropriate locking. Do not use this in plug-ins or
    applications in order to retain ABI compatibility.

    Elements can have pads (of the type :class:`Gst.Pad`).  These pads link to pads on
    other elements.  :class:`Gst.Buffer` flow between these linked pads.
    A :class:`Gst.Element` has a :class:`GList` of :class:`Gst.Pad` structures for all their input (or sink)
    and output (or source) pads.
    Core and plug-in writers can add and remove pads with :meth:`Gst.Element.add_pad`
    and :meth:`Gst.Element.remove_pad`.

    An existing pad of an element can be retrieved by name with
    :meth:`Gst.Element.get_static_pad`. A new dynamic pad can be created using
    :meth:`Gst.Element.request_pad` with a :class:`Gst.PadTemplate`.
    An iterator of all pads can be retrieved with :meth:`Gst.Element.iterate_pads`.

    Elements can be linked through their pads.
    If the link is straightforward, use the :meth:`Gst.Element.link`
    convenience function to link two elements, or gst_element_link_many()
    for more elements in a row.
    Use :meth:`Gst.Element.link_filtered` to link two elements constrained by
    a specified set of :class:`Gst.Caps`.
    For finer control, use :meth:`Gst.Element.link_pads` and
    :meth:`Gst.Element.link_pads_filtered` to specify the pads to link on
    each element by name.

    Each element has a state (see :class:`Gst.State`).  You can get and set the state
    of an element with :meth:`Gst.Element.get_state` and :meth:`Gst.Element.set_state`.
    Setting a state triggers a :class:`Gst.StateChange`. To get a string representation
    of a :class:`Gst.State`, use :func:`Gst.state_get_name`.

    You can get and set a :class:`Gst.Clock` on an element using :meth:`Gst.Element.get_clock`
    and :meth:`Gst.Element.set_clock`.
    Some elements can provide a clock for the pipeline if
    the :data:`Gst.ElementFlags.PROVIDE_CLOCK` flag is set. With the
    :meth:`Gst.Element.provide_clock` method one can retrieve the clock provided by
    such an element.
    Not all elements require a clock to operate correctly. If the
