class Promise:
    """
    The :class:`Gst.Promise` object implements the container for values that may
    be available later. i.e. a Future or a Promise in
    <https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Futures_and_promises>.
    As with all Future/Promise-like functionality, there is the concept of the
    producer of the value and the consumer of the value.

    A :class:`Gst.Promise` is created with :meth:`Gst.Promise.new` by the consumer and passed
    to the producer to avoid thread safety issues with the change callback.
    A :class:`Gst.Promise` can be replied to with a value (or an error) by the producer
    with :meth:`Gst.Promise.reply`. The exact value returned is defined by the API
    contract of the producer and ``None`` may be a valid reply.
    :meth:`Gst.Promise.interrupt` is for the consumer to
    indicate to the producer that the value is not needed anymore and producing
    that value can stop.  The ``GST_PROMISE_RESULT_EXPIRED`` state set by a call
    to :meth:`Gst.Promise.expire` indicates to the consumer that a value will never
    be produced and is intended to be called by a third party that implements
    some notion of message handling such as :class:`Gst.Bus`.
    A callback can also be installed at :class:`Gst.Promise` creation for
    result changes with :meth:`Gst.Promise.new_with_change_func`.
    The change callback can be used to chain :class:`GstPromises`'s together as in the
    following example.
    |[<!-- language="C" -->
    const :class:`Gst.Structure` *reply;
    :class:`Gst.Promise` *p;
    if (:meth:`Gst.Promise.wait` (promise) != GST_PROMISE_RESULT_REPLIED)
      return; // interrupted or expired value
    reply = :meth:`Gst.Promise.get_reply` (promise);
    if (error in reply)
      return; // propagate error
    p = :meth:`Gst.Promise.new_with_change_func` (another_promise_change_func, user_data, notify);
    pass p to promise-using API
    ]|

    Each :class:`Gst.Promise` starts out with a :class:`Gst.PromiseResult` of
    :data:`Gst.PromiseResult.PENDING` and only ever transitions once
    into one of the other :class:`Gst.PromiseResult`'s.

    In order to support multi-threaded code, :meth:`Gst.Promise.reply`,
    :meth:`Gst.Promise.interrupt` and :meth:`Gst.Promise.expire` may all be from
    different threads with some restrictions and the final result of the promise
    is whichever call is made first.  There are two restrictions on ordering:

    1. That :meth:`Gst.Promise.reply` and :meth:`Gst.Promise.interrupt` cannot be called
    after :meth:`Gst.Promise.expire`
    2. That :meth:`Gst.Promise.reply` and :meth:`Gst.Promise.interrupt`
    cannot be called twice.

    The change function set with :meth:`Gst.Promise.new_with_change_func` is
    called directly from either the :meth:`Gst.Promise.reply`,
    :meth:`Gst.Promise.interrupt` or :meth:`Gst.Promise.expire` and can be called
    from an arbitrary thread.  :class:`Gst.Promise` using APIs can restrict this to
    a single thread or a subset of threads but that is entirely up to the API
    that uses :class:`Gst.Promise`.
    """
